Zeller points out that the course of 'Erasmus' known movements in Italy, 1 506â€”9, makes it improbable that he should have visited lioretto. Possibly Bietricius, from whom the impulse certainly came, had made the pilgrimage from his distant parish and been impressed by what he had seen. It is noticeable that throughout the Liturqia Erasmus makes no allusion to the miraculous translation.

Theobald Bietricius was the parish-priest of Porrentruy, a little town 25 miles sw. of Basle, on the northern slopes of the Jura, which was formerly of some im- portance as the residence of the Bishop of Basle and one of the centres of his jurisdiction. The present dedication probably indicates that his acquaintance with Erasmus had begun in Basle. then Erasmus visited Besancon from Porrentruy in April 1524 (see Ep. 1440. 411), Bietricius accompanicd him and remained with him during his stay there. He continued a faithful friend to Erasmus z see his two letters of 21 July 1524 (Ep. 1468) and 11 Oct. 1526 (Ep. 1760). The latter is the last trane that I can find of him]
